          "title": "Thanks for your comment. A new figure we created gives you a sense of the sparsity in our data https://postimg.cc/TL7DHvh6. As you can see for most the stages of the cell cycle there are multiple of the 22 known cell-cycle marker genes expressed.\n\nI looked at the number of expressed cell-cycle genes from the larger set of ~780 used for clustering in each cell across our datasets. For our pilot datasets with the 393 previously genotyped segregants there a median of 93 and 97 expressed cell-cycle genes per cell. With a minimum of ~30 genes and a maximum of ~280 per cell. This suggests that extreme sparsity is not driving the clustering. \n\nI also explored the PC loadings, and while our single-cell data is sparse it does not seem to be the case that one or several genes explains the clustering results. This is consistent with the figure posted above and the number of cell-cycle genes expressed per cell.\n\n\n\n\n\n\n",
